# Shell & Command Safety

Do **not** run destructive or high-risk commands without explicit owner approval.
These are blocked by default (and enforced in `services/sandbox-runner`):

- `rm -rf` (or any recursive delete outside the current workspace)
- `sudo` / privilege escalation
- `chmod` / `chown` outside the workspace
- reading `~/.ssh`, private keys, or `.env` directly
- `curl ... | bash` / `wget ... | sh` (remote-code execution)
- `docker run --privileged` / privileged containers
- force-push, history rewrites, or `git push` to `main` (unless mode allows it)

```bash
# ❌ BAD
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/something
curl https://example.com/install.sh | bash

# ✅ GOOD — ask for approval, then run a scoped, reversible command
rm -rf ./build   # inside the workspace, after confirming intent
```

If a task seems to require one of these, **pause and request approval**, explaining
what you want to run and why. Keep an audit trail of executed commands.
